---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Research | Alfie McGlennon"
  description="MSc dissertation on compound heat stress risk in Europe. A copula-based framework with ML-driven dependence estimation, fitted to ERA5 and evaluated against CMIP6."
  ogTitle="Research | Alfie McGlennon"
  ogDescription="Dissertation research questions, motivation, and approach. Copulas, multiplicative bias decomposition, XGBoost for Kendall's tau."
>
  <article class="page-narrow research">
    <p class="kicker">Dissertation</p>
    <h1>Predicting Compound Heat Stress Risk in Europe: A Copula-Based Framework with ML-Driven Dependence Estimation</h1>

    <p class="lede">
      Compound heat stress happens when high temperature and high humidity
      arrive together. Most climate risk assessments treat these variables
      as independent, which recent work shows significantly underestimates
      the probability of compound events. This dissertation develops a
      framework to model, diagnose, and correct the dependence structure
      using copulas and machine learning.
    </p>

    <h2>Research questions</h2>
    <ol class="rq">
      <li>
        How does the dependence structure between temperature and dew
        point temperature vary across European regions and seasons, and
        how well does an independence assumption perform for estimating
        compound heat stress risk?
      </li>
      <li>
        Can atmospheric circulation patterns (particularly Z500) predict
        within-season variations in temperature and dew point dependence
        using machine learning?
      </li>
      <li>
        How do trends in marginal warming versus dependence evolution
        separately contribute to changes in compound heat stress risk?
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Why it matters</h2>
    <p>
      The main gap is laid out in Brett et al. (2025), <em>Review article:
      The growth in compound weather and climate event research in the
      decade since SREX</em>. The field has grown rapidly in characterising
      compound events, but very little work has moved toward predicting
      them. Most existing studies assume independence between temperature
      and dew point when estimating joint risk, which systematically
      underestimates compound heat stress probability.
    </p>
    <p>
      Dew point serves as a direct proxy for atmospheric moisture and is a
      key driver of heat stress alongside air temperature. Copulas offer a
      natural framework for modelling the dependence between these
      variables, and linking them to large-scale atmospheric circulation
      (Z500 patterns) gives the work an operational angle for sub-seasonal
      forecasting.
    </p>
    <p>
      For reinsurance and climate adaptation, the question is not just
      &lsquo;will it be hot?&rsquo; but &lsquo;will it be hot and humid at
      the same time?&rsquo; Getting that joint probability right is the
      difference between adequate and inadequate risk pricing.
    </p>

    <h2>Why I chose it</h2>
    <p>
      What drew me here was the intersection of statistics, climate
      science, and practical risk. The independence assumption is wrong in
      a way that has been repeatedly documented, yet most operational risk
      work still uses it. There is an opportunity to build something that
      bridges the academic compound-events literature and the operational
      forecasting world, and the methods involved (copulas, gradient
      boosting on circulation features) are concrete enough that the work
      can be used, not just cited.
    </p>

    <h2>Approach</h2>
    <p>The framework is built on three layers.</p>
    <ol class="rq">
      <li>
        A multiplicative decomposition of compound hazard bias:
        <code>M_total = M_marginal &times; M_dependence</code>. This
        separates errors that come from getting individual variables wrong
        (marginal bias) from errors that come from getting their
        co-occurrence wrong (dependence bias).
      </li>
      <li>
        Copula-based modelling of the dependence structure, fitted to ERA5
        reanalysis as ground truth and evaluated against CMIP6 projections.
      </li>
      <li>
        ML-driven dependence estimation using XGBoost to predict
        Kendall&rsquo;s tau from large-scale circulation features (Z500,
        MSLP, jet-stream indices), enabling dependence prediction under
        future climate scenarios.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      A detailed visual introduction to copulas, and why they matter for
      compound risk, is coming soon on the
      <a href="/writing/">Writing page</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Data</h2>
    <p>
      ERA5 reanalysis (1981 to 2020) as the ground-truth dependence
      climatology. CMIP6 projections for historical and future scenarios.
      Destination Earth (DestinE) climate digital-twin output where
      available.
    </p>

    <h2>Publication plan</h2>
    <p>
      Two papers are planned. A methods paper on the multiplicative
      decomposition framework, targeting a traditional extremes or
      statistical climatology journal. A second paper on the ML-driven
      dependence estimation, targeting the Royal Meteorological
      Society&rsquo;s special issue on Advances in Machine Learning for
      Weather and Climate, with a December 2026 deadline.
    </p>

    <hr class="research-rule" />

    <section class="other-research">
      <div class="dot" aria-hidden="true"></div>
      <p>
        Results are ongoing and will be added here as the work progresses.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>

